window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : MOTION UNDER GRAVITY","question":"A particle is dropped from a vertical height h and falls freely for a time t. With the aid of a sketch, explain how h varies with t2.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Recall: h = ut + 1/2 gt2 --------- (1)  Now, for an object which drops from rest, i.e, u = 0  h = 1/2 gt2 ---------- (2)  or   h = 0 + 1/2 gt2 -------- (3)  Equate (3) to y = mx + c  h = 1/2 gt2 + 0  y = mx + c    On the y-axis, we have h; and on the x - axis, we have t2; and m (slope) = 1/2 g","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"FINAL","topic":"PROJECTILE MOTION :","question":"A particle is projected horizontally at 15ms-1 from a height of 20m. Calculate the horizontal distance covered by the particle just before hitting the ground.  [g = 10ms-2]  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Ux = 15ms-1 (horizontal velocity)  H = 20m  R = Unknown  Diagrammatically, we have    Recall:  H = Uyt + 1/2 gt2  Uy = 0  H = 1/2 gt2 ---------------- *  20 = 1/2 \u00d7 10 \u00d7 t2  40 = 10t2  t2 = 4  t = 2s  Recall:  R = UxT  R = (15)(2) = 30m","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"List three phenomena which can be explained by the molecular theory of matter.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The following phenomena can be explained by the molecular theory of matter:  i.  Brownian movement  ii. Diffusion  iii. Effusion  iv. Osmosis  v. Viscosity  vi. Evaporation","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"FINAL","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"A spiral spring has a length of 14cm when a force of 4N is hung on it. A force of 6N extends the spring by 4cm. Calculate the unstretched length of the spring.  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Initial length = L1 = 14cm  Initial Force = F1 = 4N  When a force of 6N is applied, the extension, e = 4cm, i.e L2 = 18cm  Unstretched length, Lo = Unknown  N.B: Unstretched length = Original length  Recall;  F1L1-L0=F2L2-L1=FnLn-Ln-1  414-L0=64  16 = 6(14 - L0)   166=14-L0  L0=84-166=686=1126=1113=11.3cm","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>5>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"State two factors on which surface tension depends.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The following factors affect surface tension:  i. Nature of liquid  ii. Temperature of liquid  iii. Presence/Absence of Impurities","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>5>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF MATTER :","question":"How can mosquito larvae be made to sink in stagnant water?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"It should be noted that mosquito larva float on water, due to the surface tension of water.  Surface tension can be reduced by any of the following methods  i. Alcohol  ii. Soap/Detergent  iii. Camphor  iv. Application of heat   It implies that the above listed methods will reduce the surface tension of water and hence cause the mosquito larva to sink.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"List three advantages of fluorescent tubes over filament bulbs.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Fluorescent tubes are advantageous compared to fluorescent bulbs in the sense that, fluorescent tubes.  i. produce less heat  ii. are brighten  iii. use up less energy (electrical)","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART I>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"7","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"List three advantages of p - n junction diode over diode valve.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The advantages of p-n junction include:  1. It is cheaper  2. It requires low voltage in its operation  3. It operates at a very fast rate, i.e, it does not require time to warm up.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>8>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"POSITION, DISTANCE AND DISPLACEMENT : DISTINCTION BETWEEN DISTANCE AND DISPLACEMENT.","question":"State two deductions that can be made from a displacement-time graph.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The following deductions can be made from a displacement time graph  i. Instantaneous velocity  ii. Uniform velocity","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>8>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"GRAVITATIONAL FIELD : NEWTON\u2019S LAW OF GRAVITATION","question":"If the distance between two equal masses is doubled and their individual masses are also doubled, what would happen to the force between them? Support your answer quantitatively.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"From Newton's Law of Universal Gravitation  F=GM1M2d2  G=Fd2M1M2  It is stated in the question that the bodies have equal masses, therefore, M1 = M2 = m  G=Fd2m2  G1 = G2  F1d12m12=F2d22m22  d2 = 2d1 ----------------   m2 = 2m1 ------------- *  F1d12m12=F2(2d1)2(2m1)2  F1d12m12=F2\u00d74d124m12  F1 = F2  It implies that the initial force of attraction is equal to the final force of attraction.","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>8>c","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"State two factors that affect the maximum height attained by a bullet fired from a gun.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"An external/environmental factor which affects the maximum height is air resistance.  Other factors which affect the value of the maximum height are:  i. Angle of projection (\u03b8)  ii. Initial speed (U)  iii. Acceleration due to gravity (g)  i, ii and iii can be deduced from:  Hm=U2sin2\u03b82g--------------***","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>8>d","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : FORCED VIBRATION AND RESONANCE","question":"State two practical examples of mechanical resonance.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Examples of mechanical resonance include:  i. the collapse of a bridge caused by soldiers marching on it.  ii. Care bodies rattle  iii. the breaking of glass by high frequency vibrations","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>8>e","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"e","group":"FINAL","topic":"MOTION : CAUSE OF MOTION","question":"A body is released from rest at the top of a plane inclined at 30\u00b0 to the horizontal and 4.0m high. If the coefficient of friction between the body and the plane is 0.3, calculate the time the body takes to reach the bottom of the plane.  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Diagrammatically, the information in the question can be represented as:    \u03bc = 0.3 (co-efficient of static friction)  N.B: Two horizontal forces act on this body.  * The force acting on the body and which makes it move down the plane = mgsin\u03b8  * The opposing frictional force on the body = \u03bcmgcos\u03b8  Since mgsin\u03b8 > \u03bcmgcos\u03b8, the net force on the body is given as:  F = mgsin\u03b8 - \u03bcmgcos\u03b8 --------------- (1)  Recall: F = ma  ma = mgsin\u03b8 - \u03bcmgcos\u03b8  ma = m(gsin\u03b8 - \u03bcgcos\u03b8)  a = gsin\u03b8 - \u03bcgcos\u03b8 -------------- (2)  a = 10(sin30\u00b0) - 0.3(10cos30\u00b0)  a = 10(0.5) - 0.3(10 \u00d7 0.8660)  a = 5 - 2.6  a = 2.4m/s2  Recall: s = ut + 1/2 at2 ----------- (3)  S is the distance travelled down the plane.    From SOHCAHTOA  sin30\u00b0=45  s=4sin30\u00b0=8m  Equation (3) becomes   8 = ut + 1/2 (2.4)t2  since the body starts its motion from rest, therefore, u = 0  8 = 0(t) + 1/2 (2.4)t2  8 = 1.2t2  t2=81.2=6.67  t = &radic;6.67&nbsp; = 2.6s","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>9>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"Define stable equilibrium as applied to a rigid body.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A body is said to be in a stable equilibrium if after a slight displacement the body returns to its original position.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>9>b","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Sketch a block and tackle system of pulleys with a velocity ratio of 3.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"A block and tackle system with a velocity ratio of 3 is one that has three (3) pulleys.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>9>c","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"At the beginning of a race, a tyre of volume 8.0 \u00d7 10-4m3 at 20\u00b0C has a gas pressure of 4.5 \u00d7 105Pa. Calculate the temperature of the gas in the tyre at the end of the race if the pressure has risen to 4.6 \u00d7 105Pa.  (Leaving the answer in one decimal place)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"This question bothers on general gas equation.  V1 = 8.0 \u00d7 10-4m3  T1 = 20\u00b0C = 293K  P1 = 4.5 \u00d7 105pa  T2 = unknown  P2 = 4.6 \u00d7 105pa  The question does not say anything about the volume changing, therefore, let us assume it is constant, i.e V1 = V2  P1T1=P2T2 Pressure Law  4.5\u00d7105293=4.6\u00d7105T2  T2=4.6\u00d72934.5=299.5K(26.5\u00b0C)","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>9>d>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"Ice point 273KSteam point 373KResistance/\u03a95.677.75Pressure/Pa7.13 \u00d7 1049.74 \u00d7 104  The table above shows readings of the resistance and pressure of a platinum resistance thermometer and a constant-volume gas thermometer respectively, when immersed in the same liquid bath. Use this data to determine the temperature of the bath on the : (\u03b1) resistance thermometer;  (\u03b2) gas thermometer","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>9>d>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"By what percentage is the temperature measured on the platinum resistance thermometer in error?   (Leaving the answer in three decimal place)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>10>a","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : WAVEFORM","question":"What is a wavefront?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A wave front is a surface connecting points of equal phase on all waves in a geometric plane.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>10>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"State two practical uses of glass prisms.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The practical uses of glass prisms include:  i. Binoculars (for viewing distant objects)  ii. Periscope  iii. For the dispersion of light rays (beam)","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>10>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"List two factors that determine the deviation of a ray of light travelling from air into a triangular glass prism.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"1. The refractive index of the prism in use  2. The angle of incidence  3. The refracting angle of the prism.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>10>b>iii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Sketch a graph to illustrate the variation of the angle of deviation d, with that of incidence i, for a ray of light travelling from air into a triangular glass prism. Indicate on the graph the point at which the angle of incidence i is equal to the angle of emergence e.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"N.B: dm = Minimum deviation  i = angle of incidence  e = angle of emergence","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>10>c>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"Draw and label a diagram of an astronomical telescope in normal adjustment.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"ASTRONOMICAL TELESCOPE","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>10>c>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : APPLICATION OF LENSES IN OPTICAL INSTRUMENTS","question":"The angular magnification of an astronomical telescope in normal adjustment is 5. If the focal length of the objective is 100cm, calculate the:   (\u03b1) focal length of the eyepiece;  (\u03b2) length of the telescope.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Angular magnification = 5  Fo (objective focal length) = 100cm  \u03b1 = Fe (eye piece focal length ) = ?  LT = \u03b2 (length of telescope) = ?   Recall:  Angularmagnification=Objective Focal LengthEye piece Focal length  5=100Fe  Fe = 20cm  LT = Fo + Fe  LT = 100cm + 20cm = 120cm","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>11>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"What is dielectric?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A dielectric is a non-conducting material such as rubber, glass or waxed paper separating the two plates of a capacitor.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>11>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"A parallel plate capacitor consists of two plates each of area 9.6 \u00d7 10-2m2, separated by a dielectric of thickness 2.25 \u00d7 10-3m and dielectric constant 900. Calculate the capacitance of the capacitor.  [\u03b5o = permittivity of free space = 8.85 \u00d7 10-12Fm-1]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Area, A = 9.6 \u00d7 10-2m2  Distance d, between the plates = 2.25 \u00d7 10-3m  \u03b5r = 900  \u03b5o = 8.85 \u00d7 10-12Fm-1  Recall:C=A\u03b5o\u03b5rd---------(1)  C=9.6 \u00d7 10-2 \u00d7 8.86 \u00d7 10-12 \u00d7 9002.25 \u00d7 10-3  c = 3.4 \u00d7 10-7F","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>11>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Which of the following devices has a higher resistance; an ammeter or a voltmeter? Give a reason for your answer.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A voltmeter should have a higher resistance.  This is because an ammeter measures current, therefore it should not be constructed in such a way that the opposition to the flow of current in it will be very high.  This is why in a connection, the voltmeter is connected in parallel to allow a minimum passage of current through it.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>11>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"The resistance of the voltmeter in the circuit diagram illustrated above is 800\u03a9. Calculate the voltmeter reading.  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Two 400\u03a9 resistors are in parallel, the effective resistance, Re, can be gotten by:  1Re=1400+1400  1Re=400+400(400)(400)  Re=(400)(400)800=16\u00d71048\u00d7102=200\u03a9.  The question says the resistance of the voltmeter V is 800\u03a9, so we redraw the diagram B      Two 800\u03a9 resistors are in parallel, the effective resistance, Re, can be gotten by:  1Re=1800+1800  =800+800(800)(800)  Re=(800)(800)1600=64 \u00d7 10416 \u00d7 102  Re = 400\u03a9.  N.B: Resistors in parallel arrangement will have equal voltage (p.d). Therefore, V800\u03a9 = V800\u03a9  6V = VA + VB ---------------------- (1)  VA = IA \u00d7 200 ------------- (2)  VB = IB \u00d7 400 ---------- (3)  First calculate the total current in the circuit  Ve = Ie \u00d7 Re  6V = Ie \u00d7 (200 + 400)  Ie = 0.01A  Since the two resistors are now in series, Ie = IA = IB = 0.01A    VA = 0.01 \u00d7 200 = 2V  VB = 0.01 \u00d7 400 = 4V  The voltmeter reads 4V","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>11>c","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"A battery of negligible internal resistance is connected to a set of resistors as illustrated in the circuit diagram above. Determine the equivalent resistance of the circuit.  (Leaving the answer in whole number)","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The effective, resistance of B and C is given as:  1Re=12\u03a9+12\u03a9  1Re=2\u03a9+2\u03a9(2)(2)\u03a92  1Re=11\u03a9  Re = 1\u03a9  Re-draw the diagram    A, B and C are all in series   Re = 2\u03a9 + 2\u03a9 + 1\u03a9  Re = 5\u03a9  Now, the diagram becomes","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>12>a>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"What is nuclear fission?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Nuclear fission is a radioactive process which involves the disintegration (splitting) of heavy nucleus into lighter nuclei accompanied by energy release.","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>12>a>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : FUSION AND FISSION","question":"State the function of each of the following materials in a nuclear fission reactor;  (\u03b1) graphite;  (\u03b2) boron rods  (\u03b3) liquid sodium","images":[],"marking_scheme":"- Graphite helps to slow down neutrons in reaction chambers  - Boron rods absorbs completely the energetic neutrons so as to control fission rate  - Liquid sodium serves as a thermal conductor which conducts excess heat away from the reaction chamber.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>12>b>i","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"The table below gives some of the energy levels of a hydrogen atom.  n12345\u221eEn/eV-13.60-3.39-1.51-0.85-0.540.00    Draw the energy level diagram for the atom.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"En: n = \u03b1 -------------- 0eV  E4: n = 5 ------------- -0.54eV  E3: n = 4 ------------- -0.85eV  E2: n = 3 --------------- -1.51eV  E1; n = 2 ---------------- -3.39eV  E0; n = 1 --------------- -13.60 eV","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>12>b>ii","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : ENERGY QUANTIZATION","question":"The table below gives some of the energy levels of a hydrogen atom.  n12345\u221eEn/eV-13.60-3.39-1.51-0.85-0.540.00  Determine the wavelength of the photon emitted when the atom goes from the energy state n = 3 to the ground state.  [h = 6.6 \u00d7 10-34Js, c = 3.0 \u00d7 108ms-1, e = 1.6 \u00d7 10-19C]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Planck's constant, h = 6.6 \u00d7 10-34Js  Velocity of light, c = 3.0 \u00d7 108ms-1  Charge of electron, e = 1.60 \u00d7 10-19C  Wavelength, \u03bb = ?  Recall: \u03bb=hc\u0394E  \u03bb=6.6\u00d710-34\u00d73.0\u00d7108(-1.51-(-13.60))\u00d71.6\u00d710-19  \u03bb = 1.02 \u00d7 10-7m","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics>2017>PART II>12>c","subject":"Physics","year":"2017","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : RADIOACTIVITY","question":"A piece of ancient bone from an excavation site showed 146C activity of 9.5 disintegrations per minute per 1.0 \u00d7 10-3kg. If a bone specimen from a living creature shows 146C activity of 12.0 disintegrations per minute per 1.0 \u00d7 10-3kg, determine the age of the ancient bone.  [Half-life of 146C = 5572 years]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"\u03bb=0.693t1/2  \u03bb=0.6935572  \u03bb = 0.0001244 year-1    N = Noe-\u03bbt    1.2632 = e-0.0001244t    0.234 = 0.0001244t    \u2234 t = 1878 years","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"}];